   Benedict  , from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. In the 12th century the Latin form of the name is found in England alongside versions derived from the Old French form <i>Beneit</i>, <i>Benoit</i>, which was common among the Normans. The surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Bernhard  .","Altered form of French   Benet   or   Bennet   or of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bennet","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  .","French: derivative of   Benne  ."]},{"name":"Bennitt","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennetts","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant of   Bennett  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Dittus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Fritz, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bennette","meanings":["English (Cornwall): altered form of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennight","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Bene(i)t</i> + <i>-son</i>. See   Bennett   and compare   Benson  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":67,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":76,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Bennett was born in 1482, in Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter. She died on 20 March 1558, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1482–20 Mar 1558":"1482–20. märts 1558","1512–1560":"1512–1560","1482–1558":"1482–1558","1558":"1558","1512":"1512","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","20 Mar 1558":"20. märts 1558","1549":"1549","Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1482–20 Mar 1558":"1482–20. maaliskuuta 1558","1512–1560":"1512–1560","1482–1558":"1482–1558","1558":"1558","1512":"1512","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","20 Mar 1558":"20. maaliskuuta 1558","1549":"1549","Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1482–20 Mar 1558":"1482–20 mars 1558","1512–1560":"1512–1560","1482–1558":"1482–1558","1558":"1558","1512":"1512","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","20 Mar 1558":"20 mars 1558","1549":"1549","Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Anne Bennett est née en 1482, à Caernarfonshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée le 20 mars 1558, à Lincoln, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 76 ans."},"de":{"1482–20 Mar 1558":"1482–20. März 1558","1512–1560":"1512–1560","1482–1558":"1482–1558","1558":"1558","1512":"1512","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","20 Mar 1558":"20. März 1558","1549":"1549","Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","lifeSummary":"Anne Bennett wurde 1482 in Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb am 20. März 1558 im Alter von 76 Jahren in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England."},"ht":{"1482–20 M